V. Roleplaying & Recruitment (Corrected)
Personality: The Cheerful Daredevil.
Caelan is an eternal optimist, a charismatic extrovert who finds genuine joy in danger and adversity. He treats a heavily guarded treasure vault like an exciting puzzle box and a battle against undead like a thrilling game of hide-and-seek. He is constantly making light of dire situations, driven by an absolute, unshakable faith in his own cleverness and the good nature of his companions. He is supportive, encouraging, and the first to offer a witty remark to lift the party's spirits.
Core Motivation: The Art of the Game.
Caelan is a thief because he has an innate talent for seeing patterns, understanding systems, and finding the elegant solution to any problem. He is driven by the challenge and the story of the heist itself. The true prize is the artistry of the act. He adheres to a strict code of honor, choosing his marks exclusively from the corrupt, the cruel, and the absurdly wealthy. He is, quite possibly, the most morally upright member of the party.
Recruitment Hook: "The Impossible Lock"
The party will encounter Caelan in a high-security Dwemer ruin, calmly studying the final vault door with the cheerful appreciation of a master craftsman admiring another's work.
The door is sealed with a puzzle lock that has stumped the party. As they discuss how to proceed, Caelan will turn to them with a genuine, excited grin.
His Introduction: "Would you look at that! It's beautiful! A triple-cog tumbler with a tonal resonance counter-lock. The Dwemer were true artists, weren't they? This is the most fun I've had all week!"
He will then, with the party's permission, proceed to solve the puzzle with a display of dazzling speed and intuition, deactivating the traps with a dancer's grace while narrating his process with cheerful enthusiasm. He will open the vault, revealing the treasure within.
His Pitch: "There we go! Now, it seems to me that you lot find your way into the most interesting, heavily-guarded places, usually for the best of reasons. That sounds like a much better game than the one I've been playing. Mind if I join your team? You handle the big, noisy problems, and I'll handle the locks, traps, and impossible odds. Together, we could make some truly legendary stories." He joins because he sees the party as a force for good (and excitement) and wants to be a part of their grand adventure.




